description.text:
I merged Gargi's nema 17 back box mount and Eddima's side mounted fan into a top sitting X axis motor blower.
There isn't room (or weight allowance) for much on the printrbot head, but the extruder motor can run hot.
This is one general solution. The mount is angled about 15 degrees and moves air at the extruder head motor level from the center to the near side. This makes a decent bed fan if it is attached with the fan on the bed side, the slight angle blows into the middle of the bed. The distance makes a gentler breeze than a head mounted fan does. It slides easily on and off the motor, but is heavy enough not to rattle. The walls are much thicker on this model, there shouldn't be any thin wall problems. I have a 50mm 12 volt fan mounted. I used the fan mount from this
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24396

comments.text: I'm a bit ashamed mines not printed, but I wanted to keep thermal efficiency high. The heat sink and fan came from an Alaska Universal chip set cooling set. The extruder motor now runs completely cold.

Model of a shabti / ushabti, a funerary figure of ancient Egypt which was placed in a tomb with the deceased occupant. It was expected to take human form in the afterlife and serve it's master. Quite a few of the models are available on the University of Birmingham (UK) web site, see link below. http://mimsy.bham.ac.uk/detail.php?t=objects&type=browse&f=OBJECT_TYPE&s=Shabti&record=2

There are three stl's.
A complete one and the same model split roughly in half.
The complete one needs a support structure wheras the split one doesn't however you may have issues joining the two halves, I had to fill in the gaps with a filler before painting.
If the half models warp a little so the flat sides do not touch I have found a little trick to help (probably only works with pla).
Put the halves together and wrap an elastic band tightly round each end.
Dip one end in hot water, enough to soften the plastic.
the elastic should bring the two halves in contact but you can help by gently squeezing them together.
Repeat for the other end.
